author: Al Jazeera English
description:
TikTok, the popular short-form video app, has become a central focus in debates over technology sovereignty and global trade. Initially branded a national security threat during Trump’s first term, the app’s Chinese owner, ByteDance, was later pressured by Washington to sell its US operations or face a ban. The uncertainty continued into Trump’s second term, as negotiations over ownership and data control unfolded. A new framework eventually allowed for the majority of American investment and oversight of TikTok’s algorithm. The move was presented as protecting national interests and user data. The saga highlights the clash between freedom, control, and the influence of AI-driven platforms on young American users.

Al Jazeera’s Alex Baird takes a closer look at the geopolitical tug-of-war being fought over TikTok- and its power to influence millions.
Joining us from Danbury in Connecticut, is Bill Holstein. He is an Author, journalist and Co-author of "Battlefield Cyber: How China and
title: TikTok’s journey from a viral app to a geopolitical power struggle

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Even with a ceasefire, Palestinians in Gaza search for lost loved ones. 
Wassim Al Yaziji lost his entire family of 13 when their house in Nuseirat refugee camp was flattened by an Israeli strike.
He recalls leaving his home for his uncle's, believing it was safe. 
Moments after he stepped out, the area was carpet-bombed.
He returned after being injured to find the house destroyed, with no walls standing. 
For days, his family dug with simple tools but found no complete bodies.
They recovered only a bag of flesh and bones. His parents, siblings, and relatives have vanished, leaving him with no grave to visit to honour their memory.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
At an emergency UN Security Council meeting on Sudan, Under-Secretary-General for Humanitarian Affairs Tom Fletcher described the situation in el-Fasher as “an even darker hell,” with reports of mass executions, rape, and mutilation following the Rapid Support Forces’ assault on the city. 
Fletcher said nearly 500 people, including patients, were killed in a hospital attack, and tens of thousands have fled on foot, facing extortion and violence. 
He condemned the RSF for blocking humanitarian convoys and noted that 13.5 million people had been reached with aid despite severe restrictions. 
Fletcher announced a $20m UN emergency fund allocation to support Darfur and Kordofan, but warned that 74% of the year’s response plan remains unfunded.

title: UN relief chief condemns killings, rape and famine in El-Fasher at UNSC Sudan meeting

Harsh US sanctions, reimposed by the first Trump administration, are making it difficult, if not impossible, for healthcare workers to access the drugs and equipment they need. Although designed to apply political pressure to the communist government, in reality, the sanctions hurt civilians the most. The infant mortality rate is rising, and life expectancy is falling.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Carla grew up witnessing her father’s fight to protect Valencia’s fragile beach ecosystems. Now, as climate change warms the Mediterranean, sea turtles - driven by rising sea temperatures - have begun arriving to lay their eggs on her city’s shoreline. But the beaches they rely on are under threat. Mass tourism, unchecked development, and the recent floods are eroding these vital habitats.

At 27, Carla is an environmental lawyer and conservationist who works with her father to restore the beaches and protect turtle nests, knowing the species’ survival depends on their efforts. After the catastrophic 2024 floods, Carla rallies her community to act fast to restore Valencia’s coastline. With turtle nesting coinciding with peak tourism, Carla urgently needs volunteers to protect each nest - and time is running out.

After the Floods is a documentary film by Adriana Cardoso and Rodrigo Hernandez.
title: Turtles under threat: The race to restore Spain’s coastline | Witness Documentary

description:
Russia’s latest overnight strikes on Ukraine’s Zaporizhzhia have left multiple casualties and caused buildings to collapse as emergency crews race to find survivors. 
Children are among the injured, and widespread power cuts continue across nearly every region as Russia targets Ukraine’s energy grid ahead of winter. 
In Kyiv, residents are sheltering in metro stations amid frequent air raid sirens and missile attacks. Constant bombardment has left civilians exhausted and fearful. 
On the frontline near Pokrovsk, fighting remains intense as Russian forces press forward. 
Diplomatic efforts to end the war have shown little progress.

Al Jazeera’s Zein Basravi reports.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Almost a year after the fall of the Assad regime, Syrians are facing another fight – for justice and accountability. 

In this Start Here On-The-Road, Sandra Gathmann travels to Syria to find out how the country is confronting its past and how people are trying to rebuild their lives after years of war. 

Up to 300,000 people in Syria are missing and there are thought to be as many as 66 mass graves across the country. We meet Wafa Ali Mustafa, as she faces up to the reality that her father, who’s been missing for twelve years, is most likely dead.
 
We go inside the newly-opened Syrian Identification Centre, where forensic scientists are carrying out painstaking work to identify bodies. And in an exclusive interview, we introduce one of Syria’s “shadow warriors” – a lawyer who risked his life to help smuggle out 1.3 million documents, creating an archive of evidence that links war crimes to regime officials at the highest levels, right up to Bashar al-Assad himself. 

Start Here also
title: Inside Syria’s urgent fight for justice | Start Here

description:
Palestinians in Gaza say they are losing hope in the ceasefire deal.
Many are once again picking up what little remains of their belongings, a day after waves of Israeli strikes killed more than 100 people.

description:
The leaders of the world's two biggest economies have wrapped up trade talks in South Korea.  
US President Donald Trump says his meeting with Chinese leader Xi Jinping was a “great success” and that he'll head to China in April.
During a meeting in Busan that lasted an hour and 40 minutes, the two leaders made a number of decisions on tariffs and trade.
Trump says China will begin buying US soybeans immediately and there will be no more roadblocks on rare earth minerals. 

Al Jazeera’s Rob McBride has the latest from Busan, South Korea and Katrina Yu is monitoring developments in Beijing, China.

description:
US President Donald Trump and China's leader, Xi Jinping are sitting down for high-stakes talks in the South Korean city of Busan.
The trade war between the two superpowers that's rattled the global economy is expected to top the agenda.
Just ahead of the meeting, Trump said he thinks there's a good chance of doing a deal with Beijing.
Earlier this month Trump levied additional tariffs of 100 percent on imports from China, in retaliation for Beijing curbing its rare earth exports.
Both men expressed optimism as they began their talks.

Yun Sun, the director of the Stimson Center’s China Program, explains what might happen if a deal can't be reached.
